Ask them these three things:

What jobs do you need to do around [what your industry/product/problem is]? Have them walk you through their process and record the exact words they use. For example, if you‚Äôre selling an HR solution that helps companies hire qualified people faster online, the tasks a business owner, manager or HR person need to do is create a job posting, sort through resumes, figure out interview questions, and spend hours interviewing people.

What‚Äôs hard about those jobs? Let them rant about how hard they work and what grinds their gears, how they‚Äôve failed or got outcomes they didn‚Äôt want. Record everything.

If those issues were magically solved ‚Äì what do they love about their jobs? What would they love about their lives? What would solving that problem allow them to do with that time instead?

Sure, there are a million and more questions you could ask ‚Äì but these three focus on what jobs these customers need to do, what their pain points are surrounding those jobs, and what their ideal outcomes are.

The answers you gain will start to show you some truths about your hypotheses.

You‚Äôll start to see that some kind of ‚Äòideal customers‚Äô are more ideal than others.

You‚Äôll check whether the problems they have match the problems you think they have.

You‚Äôll compare the language you use to describe those jobs and problems with the language they use.

And you‚Äôll uncover insights you can‚Äôt even begin to guess at right now.

You may have to go back to the drawing board and re-write your ideal customer hypothesis ‚Äì and that‚Äôs okay. It‚Äôs progress.

And you‚Äôll definitely come away with language you can use for marketing ‚Äì it‚Äôs one of the most valuables takeaways of this exercise.

üíó Don‚Äôt be Lazy

Why can‚Äôt you just send a survey? Hey, that‚Äôs the reaction of most founders, too. Really. If we all agreed to just keep things simple by communicating via text message and Slack, we‚Äôd have more time for everything else. But believe us when we say: You need to hear their words.

In person, if possible.

