Yes, it takes time and it‚Äôs nerve-wracking and uncomfortable. But it‚Äôs worth it. People will not tell you on a survey what they will say to your face. They won‚Äôt even tell an employee of yours the same thing they‚Äôll tell you, the founder. With an actual conversation, you‚Äôll be able to ask in-the-moment follow-up questions, listen to the tone of their answers and put their words into an emotional context, and most importantly ‚Äì you‚Äôll be starting a relationship with potentially ideal customers who might become your first customers. Your best customers. Customers that will adopt early and advocate for you.

All of this comes from person-to-person communication. You can‚Äôt survey it away.



üíó Keep it Short

A few rules for polite customer research:

Keep it short ‚Äì stick to 15 or 20 minutes. It‚Äôs enough to get deep information without scaring people away.

Make sure every question you ask is actionable ‚Äì as in, if you don‚Äôt plan to act on the information you get, don‚Äôt waste time asking the question.

Avoid yes/no questions. The goal is to get voice-of-customer data, which means you need to let them speak and not put words into their mouths.

Don‚Äôt take anything personally. These people want solutions to their problems, and maybe you have them, but even if you don‚Äôt, they‚Äôre giving you valuable feedback.

Show appreciation somehow. This doesn‚Äôt need to be fancy or expensive, but it should be personal and helpful.


üíó Sort Your Answer Pile

In the course of customer research, you‚Äôll speak with people who may have seemed like ideal customers at first, but then clearly were not.

And others who aren‚Äôt so clear. They could go either way.

The answers you need most are the ones from your ideal clients, and to make sure you‚Äôre sorting the Ideals from the Non-Ideals accurately, ask yourself this:

If I gave this person my product/service/solution, could they successfully use it to reach their ideal outcomes.

This is a Customer Success approach that I really like because it sets you up to work with people who are primed and ready to love your product (and tell their friends about it). It‚Äôs also a way to avoid The Product Death Cycle.

